In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to assert a type for a value that is not of that type. For example, you can write:
```
const value: any = "hello";
value as string; // this will assert that value is of type string
```
This is useful when you know that a value will only have a certain type, but TypeScript does not know that.

Alternatively, you can use the `type` keyword to define a new type that is a subset of the original type. For example:
```
type MyType = {
    a: string;
    b: number;
} & {
    c: string;
}
const value: MyType = { a: "hello", c: "world" };
```
This creates a new type `MyType` that is a subset of the original type `{ a: string; b: number; c: string; }`. The `type` keyword is used to create a new type that is a subset of the original type.

